WEBVTT

00:05.839 --> 00:12.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:12.846 --> 00:14.806
<i>- My name is Ben Swapp.</i>

00:14.806 --> 00:16.934
I'm 27 years old and I'm from
Albuquerque, New Mexico.

00:16.934 --> 00:18.519
<i>I'm gonna win</i>
<i>this competition</i>

00:18.519 --> 00:20.354
<i>because I'm great</i>
<i>under pressure.</i>

00:20.354 --> 00:21.605
<i>I feel like</i>
<i>anything they throw at me--</i>

00:21.605 --> 00:23.190
<i>I should be able to do it,</i>

00:23.190 --> 00:25.317
because I'm damn good
at what I do.

00:25.317 --> 00:27.277
<i>- My name is Phillip Baldwin.</i>

00:27.277 --> 00:29.238
<i>Fame is a curious thing.</i>

00:29.238 --> 00:32.282
Being a winner in this show
might be a game-changer,

00:32.282 --> 00:34.201
and I don't really have
that much time left.

00:34.201 --> 00:35.827
I'm old.

00:35.827 --> 00:37.204
<i>- My first name is Doran.</i>

00:37.204 --> 00:39.289
My last name is Doran.

00:39.289 --> 00:40.582
<i>I've gone through hell.</i>

00:40.582 --> 00:42.417
<i>I've walked a road of fire.</i>

00:42.417 --> 00:44.836
I've been forged
into a tempered blade myself,

00:44.836 --> 00:47.589
<i>and if I won $10,000,</i>

00:47.589 --> 00:50.342
I'd get me some new teeth!

00:50.342 --> 00:52.511
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Johnathan Sibley.</i>

00:52.511 --> 00:54.263
I really want to do well,

00:54.263 --> 00:56.014
mostly for my kids.

00:56.014 --> 00:57.849
<i>I regularly catch both</i>

00:57.849 --> 01:00.060
playing "Forged in Fire"
in the playroom.

01:00.060 --> 01:01.728
My daughter loves to be Wil,

01:01.728 --> 01:04.064
because Wil's the loudest.

01:04.064 --> 01:07.776
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:07.776 --> 01:10.445
You've volunteered to engage
in three timed rounds

01:10.445 --> 01:11.989
of bladesmithing competition

01:11.989 --> 01:14.032
in the hopes of
winning $10,000

01:14.032 --> 01:16.118
and the title of
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:16.118 --> 01:18.787
all in front of our panel
of expert judges,

01:18.787 --> 01:20.664
so let's meet them now.

01:20.664 --> 01:23.375
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion, Ben Abbott,

01:23.375 --> 01:25.502
historic weapons re-creation
specialist,

01:25.502 --> 01:27.004
David Baker,

01:27.004 --> 01:28.547
edged and impact weapons
specialist

01:28.547 --> 01:29.881
Doug Marcaida.

01:29.881 --> 01:31.967
Okay, gentlemen.

01:31.967 --> 01:33.844
Usually, in the first round,
what we have you do

01:33.844 --> 01:36.138
is make a signature blade
in your signature style,

01:36.138 --> 01:38.807
but today, we're making
it harder on you.

01:38.807 --> 01:40.267
You'll be forging
David Baker's

01:40.267 --> 01:41.393
favorite fighting knife.

01:41.393 --> 01:44.313
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:44.313 --> 01:45.689
- Scottish dirk.

01:45.689 --> 01:47.399
Dave Baker's
favorite weapon?

01:47.399 --> 01:49.651
<i>How cool is that?</i>

01:49.651 --> 01:51.403
- Bladesmiths,
your first round challenge

01:51.403 --> 01:53.447
is to forge a Scottish dirk

01:53.447 --> 01:55.615
that falls within
the following parameters:

01:55.615 --> 01:57.034
the blade must have
a single edge,

01:57.034 --> 01:58.577
along with a false edge

01:58.577 --> 02:00.787
that covers at least
1/3 of the spine

02:00.787 --> 02:04.541
with decorative file work,
in addition to a through tang.

02:04.541 --> 02:05.834
Today, we're not waiting
until round three

02:05.834 --> 02:07.753
to kick things up a notch.

02:07.753 --> 02:09.379
The Scottish dirk,
a blade that's both challenging

02:09.379 --> 02:11.506
in design and parameters,
is as difficult

02:11.506 --> 02:13.383
as some of our
round three weapons.

02:13.383 --> 02:15.052
Keep in mind
that in the second round,

02:15.052 --> 02:16.637
you'll be affixing handles
to your blades

02:16.637 --> 02:18.180
to turn them into
fully functional

02:18.180 --> 02:19.681
fighting knives
that will be tested

02:19.681 --> 02:21.016
for strength and durability

02:21.016 --> 02:22.893
<i>piercing an oil drum,</i>

02:22.893 --> 02:25.520
<i>and for sharpness</i>
<i>in an apple slice.</i>

02:25.520 --> 02:27.522
You will have three hours

02:27.522 --> 02:29.733
in which to forge
those blades.

02:29.733 --> 02:32.527
Now, on your anvils
is a cloth.

02:32.527 --> 02:34.154
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:34.154 --> 02:36.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:36.281 --> 02:39.076
That is 52100 steel,

02:39.076 --> 02:41.995
which you will use
to forge your Scottish dirks.

02:41.995 --> 02:44.998
<i>- Not thrilled to see</i>
<i>the big ball of 52100,</i>

02:44.998 --> 02:47.668
because balls don't like
to stay where you put 'em,

02:47.668 --> 02:50.962
and 52100 doesn't like
to move under the hammer.

02:50.962 --> 02:53.131
- Keep in mind that after
the first round is over,

02:53.131 --> 02:54.841
and the judges
have inspected your work,

02:54.841 --> 02:57.552
one of you will be asked
to surrender your work

02:57.552 --> 02:59.846
and leave The Forge.

02:59.846 --> 03:01.264
Good luck,
bladesmiths.

03:01.264 --> 03:04.559
Your three hours starts...
now.

03:04.559 --> 03:06.561
Dave, let's talk a little bit
about that dirk

03:06.561 --> 03:08.897
and what it's specifically
to be used for.

03:08.897 --> 03:10.732
- It's carried
as an all-around knife,

03:10.732 --> 03:12.901
but it's really designed
as a fighting knife.

03:12.901 --> 03:16.571
That false edge allows for
a beautiful stabbing blade.

03:16.571 --> 03:18.240
<i>- I've never made</i>
<i>a Scottish dirk,</i>

03:18.240 --> 03:20.117
<i>but I'm somewhat</i>
<i>familiar with them.</i>

03:20.117 --> 03:21.535
Well, this is gonna be fun.

03:21.535 --> 03:23.120
<i>First time I ever encountered</i>

03:23.120 --> 03:25.247
<i>52100 was two days ago,</i>

03:25.247 --> 03:27.249
when I found a bearing
in my scrap pile

03:27.249 --> 03:29.334
and said, "I think
I'd better play with this."

03:29.334 --> 03:32.129
<i>52100 is very stiff material.</i>

03:32.129 --> 03:35.799
This metal does not move
very quickly under a hammer.

03:35.799 --> 03:37.426
<i>I am very much worried about</i>

03:37.426 --> 03:38.510
running out of time.

03:38.510 --> 03:42.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:42.180 --> 03:45.016
- I think the material
is the largest challenge

03:45.016 --> 03:47.477
in the construction
of this weapon.

03:47.477 --> 03:50.897
52100's high-maintenance
and picky.

03:50.897 --> 03:52.816
<i>It's like baking cheesecake.</i>

03:52.816 --> 03:55.152
When it's done right,
it's great,

03:55.152 --> 03:57.779
<i>but it's so easy</i>
<i>to not do it right.</i>

03:57.779 --> 03:58.905
My biggest concern

03:58.905 --> 04:00.115
is this three-inch ball's

04:00.115 --> 04:03.160
gonna take forever to get hot.

04:03.160 --> 04:05.036
<i>- [imitating Scottish accent]</i>
<i>Now, a Scottish dirk</i>

04:05.036 --> 04:06.413
is something you're
gonna be wearing in your kilt,

04:06.413 --> 04:07.581
right here,
tucked into your boot.

04:07.581 --> 04:09.791
<i>It's all-around weapon</i>

04:09.791 --> 04:11.835
for the Scots' nobility,
not the peasants.

04:11.835 --> 04:13.503
- You know
what I like about this?

04:13.503 --> 04:15.505
We have one of
Dave's favorite blades here,

04:15.505 --> 04:17.466
and he'll give
a commentary on it

04:17.466 --> 04:19.676
while not wearing pants.
- [laughs]

04:19.676 --> 04:21.636
- So which part of that
was your favorite part?

04:21.636 --> 04:23.680
- It's Dave.
He can wear a kilt.

04:23.680 --> 04:25.766
I wanted to wear a kilt,

04:25.766 --> 04:28.560
but I got too fat
for my kilt.

04:28.560 --> 04:29.728
[laughs]

04:29.728 --> 04:32.439
- Welding!

04:32.439 --> 04:33.940
I've never made a blade

04:33.940 --> 04:34.983
out of a three-inch
ball bearing.

04:34.983 --> 04:36.777
I'm gonna wait on this

04:36.777 --> 04:39.196
until it's almost white
on the outside,

04:39.196 --> 04:40.697
then I plan on
beating the crap

04:40.697 --> 04:41.990
out of that steel.

04:41.990 --> 04:44.951
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:44.951 --> 04:46.828
- You want that yellow glow

04:46.828 --> 04:48.079
when it comes out of
the forge,

04:48.079 --> 04:49.498
before you start hitting it.

04:49.498 --> 04:51.041
As you're working it,

04:51.041 --> 04:52.042
as soon as it
starts losing color,

04:52.042 --> 04:54.294
back in the forge.

04:54.294 --> 04:55.670
- This challenge is perfect for

04:55.670 --> 04:57.964
this Scotch-Irish here.

04:57.964 --> 05:00.759
- Bladesmiths!
30 minutes has already elapsed!

05:00.759 --> 05:02.886
- Scottish dirk--
it's basically a bowie knife

05:02.886 --> 05:04.137
<i>made from Scotland.</i>
<i>The judges want me</i>

05:04.137 --> 05:05.931
to do this in three hours.

05:05.931 --> 05:07.641
It's gonna take every minute
to finish that.

05:07.641 --> 05:09.142
<i>It's a straight blade,</i>

05:09.142 --> 05:10.560
<i>but I'm having too much curve</i>

05:10.560 --> 05:12.395
<i>in the cutting edge of it.</i>

05:12.395 --> 05:14.064
<i>I have to make everything</i>
<i>straight.</i>

05:14.064 --> 05:15.232
<i>I go back to the power hammer,</i>

05:15.232 --> 05:16.900
and it's working well,

05:16.900 --> 05:19.027
but it's starting
to curve the blade again,

05:19.027 --> 05:20.695
<i>and in my mind, I'm like,</i>
<i>"That looks pretty cool,"</i>

05:20.695 --> 05:21.696
<i>but I realize...</i>

05:21.696 --> 05:23.532
Ugh. Okay.

05:23.532 --> 05:26.993
Stop making a bowie
and make a Scottish dirk!

05:26.993 --> 05:28.703
<i>- I like to make</i>
<i>the tang first,</i>

05:28.703 --> 05:31.248
because it give me something
to grab ahold of.

05:31.248 --> 05:32.749
- I love that he's drawing
out that tang to shape

05:32.749 --> 05:34.292
with big blue.

05:34.292 --> 05:37.087
Virtually forging
straight to shape.

05:37.087 --> 05:38.672
<i>- I've never made a knife</i>

05:38.672 --> 05:40.924
<i>to somebody else's</i>
<i>specifications.</i>

05:40.924 --> 05:43.260
I've marked my knife
where the false edge should be,

05:43.260 --> 05:46.763
<i>but whether I read</i>
<i>this ruler right or not</i>

05:46.763 --> 05:48.431
is another story altogether.

05:48.431 --> 05:51.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:51.726 --> 05:54.312
- We've asked him to do
that 1/3 false edge,

05:54.312 --> 05:56.940
which usually is what's
described as a dirk blade.

05:56.940 --> 05:59.693
<i>- We have to have</i>
<i>at least 1/3</i>

05:59.693 --> 06:00.694
<i>of the length</i>

06:00.694 --> 06:02.070
have a false edge

06:02.070 --> 06:03.697
and at least 1/3
of the length

06:03.697 --> 06:05.532
<i>have file work.</i>

06:05.532 --> 06:07.617
Whoo-hoo! "At least."

06:07.617 --> 06:08.952
I don't have to measure
anything.

06:08.952 --> 06:10.620
<i>- A false edge generally</i>

06:10.620 --> 06:11.913
<i>is put on for</i>
<i>two main reasons.</i>

06:11.913 --> 06:13.290
<i>One, they do help in stabbing,</i>

06:13.290 --> 06:14.583
and the other is that they--

06:14.583 --> 06:15.917
they look snazzy.

06:15.917 --> 06:17.794
<i>- I'm grinding my false edge,</i>

06:17.794 --> 06:19.504
<i>making sure I'm over 1/3,</i>

06:19.504 --> 06:20.797
<i>I get really close to 1/2,</i>

06:20.797 --> 06:23.592
which is still over 1/3,

06:23.592 --> 06:27.012
but I'm not anywhere near
finished.

06:27.012 --> 06:29.180
<i>I need to get this done.</i>

06:29.180 --> 06:32.017
- Bladesmiths!
Two hours has elapsed!

06:32.017 --> 06:33.935
You have 60 minutes remaining

06:33.935 --> 06:35.020
to finish your work!

06:35.020 --> 06:37.564
- Yay!

06:37.564 --> 06:39.190
I'm having a blast
making this blade.

06:39.190 --> 06:40.483
I don't know about you guys,

06:40.483 --> 06:42.485
but I think this is awesome!

06:42.485 --> 06:44.029
- Doran doesn't seem to have

06:44.029 --> 06:46.573
a dirk point on his blade.
- No.

06:46.573 --> 06:47.782
- He's got a bit of a

06:47.782 --> 06:49.034
chopper point on there.

06:49.034 --> 06:51.661
- This man's using a hammer!

06:51.661 --> 06:53.580
Well, that looks
like hammered [bleep].

06:53.580 --> 06:56.041
<i>- Johnathan and Ben</i>
<i>have that dirk look.</i>

06:56.041 --> 06:58.126
<i>Same with Phil.</i>
<i>They all drop to the point.</i>

06:58.126 --> 07:00.086
- Yes.
- It really is concerning

07:00.086 --> 07:02.422
<i>that Doran's</i>
<i>doesn't look like a dirk.</i>

07:02.422 --> 07:05.717
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:05.717 --> 07:07.761
<i>- I feel like I got it</i>
<i>all forged out correctly.</i>

07:07.761 --> 07:10.263
I need to do the file work.
I've never done it before.

07:10.263 --> 07:13.058
52100 is not all that soft.

07:13.058 --> 07:14.809
I mean, if they take
"file work" literally

07:14.809 --> 07:16.728
in their head,
it's some hard stuff, you know?

07:16.728 --> 07:19.022
<i>You're not gonna get much cut</i>
<i>with a file.</i>

07:19.022 --> 07:21.483
<i>- I'm not sure how to make</i>
<i>intricate patterns,</i>

07:21.483 --> 07:23.234
<i>so I decided that I just need</i>

07:23.234 --> 07:25.195
maybe a round
and a triangle,

07:25.195 --> 07:26.988
<i>a round and a triangle,</i>

07:26.988 --> 07:29.115
and hopefully it makes
some type of pattern.

07:29.115 --> 07:31.201
I'm just hoping
that this is good enough

07:31.201 --> 07:32.744
for the judges to say,

07:32.744 --> 07:34.162
"Yeah, this is legit
file work."

07:34.162 --> 07:36.706
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:36.706 --> 07:38.625
<i>- It's time to get</i>
<i>this heat treat done.</i>

07:38.625 --> 07:39.876
I do not want to see

07:39.876 --> 07:41.294
Dave slam his head on the table

07:41.294 --> 07:42.629
on my account.

07:42.629 --> 07:45.757
- Johnathan, quenched.

07:45.757 --> 07:48.510
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:48.510 --> 07:52.097
<i>- But I did not get the huge,</i>
<i>beautiful, volcanic fire,</i>

07:52.097 --> 07:54.474
but that's okay,

07:54.474 --> 07:56.101
'cause I still got
my eyebrows.

07:56.101 --> 07:59.187
- Yay!
- All right.

07:59.187 --> 08:00.939
- I've got the file work done,

08:00.939 --> 08:03.733
I decide, "Hey,
I'm ready for a quench."

08:03.733 --> 08:06.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:06.152 --> 08:07.904
- Ben just quenched.
- Ben to the quench.

08:07.904 --> 08:10.198
- Excellent.

08:10.198 --> 08:13.118
- I'm feeling like
I did this perfect,

08:13.118 --> 08:14.786
<i>but it's not hard.</i>

08:14.786 --> 08:16.371
What am I doing wrong?

08:16.371 --> 08:18.164
- Let it sit, Ben.
It'll get harder.

08:18.164 --> 08:19.541
It is not yet cool enough
to be hard.

08:19.541 --> 08:20.917
- No.

08:20.917 --> 08:22.419
- Am I gonna be the guy that

08:22.419 --> 08:24.754
doesn't get this hard,
and I'm out?

08:24.754 --> 08:25.839
<i>This is supposed to get hard,</i>

08:25.839 --> 08:28.466
and it's not getting hard.

08:28.466 --> 08:30.301
- No. Uh-oh.
No, no, no, no, no.

08:30.301 --> 08:32.721
You're fine. Don't do it.
Ben's file testing

08:32.721 --> 08:34.347
really fast.
- Yep.

08:34.347 --> 08:35.515
- If you're bringing it
out of the oil

08:35.515 --> 08:37.392
at 700, 800, 900 degrees,

08:37.392 --> 08:39.602
and checking it with a file,
it's not gonna be hard.

08:39.602 --> 08:42.147
I think we're gonna see Ben
go for another quench here.

08:42.147 --> 08:44.232
- I just want him to leave it
a little while longer.

08:44.232 --> 08:47.110
- Do not file check right now.

08:47.110 --> 08:49.112
- Let it sit. Let it cool.
- Yep.

08:49.112 --> 08:50.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:50.780 --> 08:51.948
- I've quenched it twice.

08:51.948 --> 08:53.450
<i>It's not getting hard.</i>

08:53.450 --> 08:55.201
- If he tries to get
that blade hotter

08:55.201 --> 08:56.745
in order to get it hard,

08:56.745 --> 08:58.204
he's making the blade brittle,
isn't he?

08:58.204 --> 08:59.539
- He runs the risk
of bringing in

08:59.539 --> 09:00.957
more stress fractures.

09:00.957 --> 09:02.417
- Do you think that Ben is

09:02.417 --> 09:03.418
making a critical mistake
right here?

09:03.418 --> 09:05.587
- I do.

09:05.587 --> 09:07.839
<i>- Not sure what to do</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

09:07.839 --> 09:09.257
<i>I'm going for</i>
<i>the third quench.</i>

09:09.257 --> 09:13.136
If this doesn't take
the quench,

09:13.136 --> 09:14.220
it's over for me.

09:14.220 --> 09:16.628
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:20.477 --> 09:22.854
<i>I let it cool down.</i>

09:22.854 --> 09:24.064
- Oh, I he--
that sounds good!

09:24.064 --> 09:25.190
- There you go!

09:25.190 --> 09:26.107
- Don't shake your head.

09:26.107 --> 09:27.650
Just go to grinding.

09:27.650 --> 09:29.444
- My file,
it skates across it,

09:29.444 --> 09:32.655
and I'm like,
"Thank goodness!"

09:32.655 --> 09:35.200
<i>- I have done</i>
<i>a fair amount of file work,</i>

09:35.200 --> 09:36.785
<i>but these files</i>
<i>are not working</i>

09:36.785 --> 09:38.578
<i>the way I want them to.</i>

09:38.578 --> 09:40.288
The files are skittering

09:40.288 --> 09:43.333
out of the channels
that I'm putting them in.

09:43.333 --> 09:45.752
<i>I'm taking too much time</i>
<i>on the file work.</i>

09:45.752 --> 09:47.587
- I'm fascinated,
watching Phil work.

09:47.587 --> 09:51.007
It's so precise,
but he still needs to quench.

09:51.007 --> 09:53.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:53.301 --> 09:54.928
- I always assume
that I have one chance

09:54.928 --> 09:56.471
<i>to heat-treat a blade,</i>

09:56.471 --> 09:57.847
because reheating, usually,

09:57.847 --> 09:59.015
is not a good idea.

09:59.015 --> 10:00.183
- There you go. Perfect.

10:00.183 --> 10:02.102
- Beautiful
- Wow.

10:02.102 --> 10:04.145
Beautiful temperature
for a quench.

10:04.145 --> 10:06.272
<i>- If it cracks, it's dead.</i>

10:06.272 --> 10:07.690
<i>That's it, we're done.</i>

10:07.690 --> 10:11.069
I'm just hoping
it doesn't warp.

10:11.069 --> 10:12.737
<i>It appears to be straight.</i>

10:12.737 --> 10:14.114
Yahoo.

10:14.114 --> 10:15.365
[laughs]

10:15.365 --> 10:17.075
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:17.075 --> 10:18.701
- I have minutes
to get this thing done.

10:18.701 --> 10:20.203
<i>I'm looking</i>
<i>at the temperature,</i>

10:20.203 --> 10:21.996
I'm looking at the color,
I don't know

10:21.996 --> 10:25.458
this steel that well,
but I have to quench now.

10:25.458 --> 10:27.043
- There you go.
- Doran, into the fire

10:27.043 --> 10:27.961
for a quench.

10:27.961 --> 10:30.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:30.130 --> 10:32.006
- The problem is,
if it keeps reigniting...

10:32.006 --> 10:33.133
- Aah!
- You know it's hot enough

10:33.133 --> 10:34.300
to ignite the oil.

10:34.300 --> 10:35.677
Put it back in the oil.

10:35.677 --> 10:37.262
- Agh!

10:37.262 --> 10:38.847
- It's still red-hot.
Get it in the oil.

10:38.847 --> 10:40.723
- Not liking that.

10:40.723 --> 10:41.808
- Now he's checking
the hardness.

10:41.808 --> 10:43.726
The thing is still red.

10:43.726 --> 10:46.020
- I'm not happy.
Time's running out.

10:46.020 --> 10:47.397
<i>I have to re-quench,</i>

10:47.397 --> 10:48.648
and if that doesn't work,

10:48.648 --> 10:49.691
I'm done.

10:49.691 --> 10:51.943
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:51.943 --> 10:55.530
- Five, four, three,

10:55.530 --> 10:59.325
two, one!

10:59.325 --> 11:00.869
- Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

11:00.869 --> 11:02.245
drop your tools!

11:02.245 --> 11:03.705
- Whoo! Hell yeah.

11:03.705 --> 11:05.915
- This round is over!

11:05.915 --> 11:07.167
<i>- My blade is on the anvil.</i>

11:07.167 --> 11:08.501
I'm looking at the file work,

11:08.501 --> 11:10.503
<i>and I see a crack.</i>

11:10.503 --> 11:14.048
I hope that it's not that big
of a deal, that I'm out.

11:14.048 --> 11:16.634
- Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

11:16.634 --> 11:18.553
each of you
made a Scottish dirk,

11:18.553 --> 11:20.889
Dave Baker's
favorite fighting knife.

11:20.889 --> 11:23.766
Now it's time for the judges
to examine your work.

11:23.766 --> 11:25.351
Ben, you're up first.

11:25.351 --> 11:27.145
Please present your blade
to the judges.

11:27.145 --> 11:30.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:30.231 --> 11:31.566
<i>- I like how you</i>
<i>put your false edge.</i>

11:31.566 --> 11:33.234
<i>It's very aggressive in that.</i>

11:33.234 --> 11:34.819
It's a very beautiful-looking
blade.

11:34.819 --> 11:36.863
- Ben, you got cracks.

11:36.863 --> 11:39.282
The crack here at the tang
is worrisome,

11:39.282 --> 11:41.284
<i>which is a critical part</i>
<i>of that blade.</i>

11:41.284 --> 11:42.827
If you move forward,

11:42.827 --> 11:44.454
it's gonna have to be
addressed.

11:44.454 --> 11:46.080
- Phil, you're up next.

11:46.080 --> 11:47.916
Please present your blade
to the judges.

11:47.916 --> 11:51.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:51.336 --> 11:53.254
<i>- When I see a dirk,</i>

11:53.254 --> 11:55.632
<i>this is very much the shape</i>
<i>I like to see.</i>

11:55.632 --> 11:58.259
It's got a very acute point
for thrusting,

11:58.259 --> 12:01.137
but there's enough mass
in that blade for a chop.

12:01.137 --> 12:02.639
<i>Bit of a warp in your tang.</i>

12:02.639 --> 12:04.974
Other than that,
absolutely gorgeous.

12:04.974 --> 12:06.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:06.601 --> 12:07.769
- Doran, you're up.
Please present

12:07.769 --> 12:10.897
your work to the judges.

12:10.897 --> 12:13.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:13.816 --> 12:15.777
<i>- Well, Doran, you've</i>
<i>turned in a solid piece.</i>

12:15.777 --> 12:17.528
<i>You know, with 52100,</i>

12:17.528 --> 12:18.738
you're always worried
about the cracks,

12:18.738 --> 12:20.531
but you maintained your heat,

12:20.531 --> 12:22.116
and that's one of the things
I like about your blade.

12:22.116 --> 12:23.952
I do not see any cracks at all.

12:23.952 --> 12:25.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:25.495 --> 12:26.454
- All right.

12:26.454 --> 12:28.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:28.206 --> 12:29.457
You've got a flat spine,

12:29.457 --> 12:31.292
and that rises towards the tip.

12:31.292 --> 12:33.628
Most of the dirks
drop towards the tip.

12:33.628 --> 12:35.255
That's kind of missing
in your design.

12:35.255 --> 12:37.131
It's not the typical dirk point

12:37.131 --> 12:38.716
that I was expecting to see.

12:38.716 --> 12:40.301
- All right, Johnathan,
you're up.

12:40.301 --> 12:41.928
Please present your blade
to the judges.

12:43.346 --> 12:44.931
<i>- I like the shape</i>
<i>of your blade.</i>

12:44.931 --> 12:46.891
<i>It's got that classic dirk</i>
<i>shape.</i>

12:46.891 --> 12:48.643
<i>It does drop to the front,</i>
<i>has a false edge,</i>

12:48.643 --> 12:51.229
but there's some surface
cracking on this blade here.

12:51.229 --> 12:53.189
It would be nice to see
if you can grind them away,

12:53.189 --> 12:54.565
but other than that,
it's a dirk.

12:54.565 --> 12:55.858
Well done.

12:55.858 --> 12:57.568
- All right, bladesmiths,

12:57.568 --> 12:58.987
the judges now have
a decision to make

12:58.987 --> 13:00.363
about who moves on
to the next round

13:00.363 --> 13:01.864
and who has to leave The Forge.

13:01.864 --> 13:03.241
While they do that,
I'm gonna ask you

13:03.241 --> 13:04.659
to step off The Forge floor.

13:04.659 --> 13:09.122
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:09.122 --> 13:10.581
<i>All right, judges.</i>

13:10.581 --> 13:12.250
It's time to get into
the details.

13:12.250 --> 13:14.127
<i>We're gonna start with</i>
<i>Ben's blade.</i>

13:14.127 --> 13:16.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:16.129 --> 13:17.714
<i>- For me, the big, big thing</i>
<i>are the cracks.</i>

13:17.714 --> 13:19.299
The multiple quenches
that he did because

13:19.299 --> 13:20.883
he was file checking
too early

13:20.883 --> 13:22.719
led to a lot of this problem.

13:22.719 --> 13:24.178
- So you didn't see
that crack at all--

13:24.178 --> 13:26.347
- I saw a crack in the spine,

13:26.347 --> 13:28.182
but I didn't see it
in the tang.

13:28.182 --> 13:30.059
- Not only just having
cracks on the blade,

13:30.059 --> 13:32.228
but at very critical junctures,

13:32.228 --> 13:34.689
right on the spine,
especially right here,

13:34.689 --> 13:37.358
in the area where, you know,
it meets the tang.

13:37.358 --> 13:39.485
I mean, that's a big structure
thing when you're chopping.

13:39.485 --> 13:41.446
Those cracks are in areas
that are just--

13:41.446 --> 13:43.364
we've seen cause
a lot of problems.

13:43.364 --> 13:45.199
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:45.199 --> 13:47.035
- All right, let's move on
to our next bladesmith,

13:47.035 --> 13:48.703
<i>and that's Phil.</i>

13:48.703 --> 13:50.747
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:50.747 --> 13:52.290
<i>- This is an example.</i>

13:52.290 --> 13:54.250
This is what all of these
should be.

13:54.250 --> 13:56.502
You know, he's got a little bit
of a warp in the tang,

13:56.502 --> 13:58.004
but it's way back here.

13:58.004 --> 13:59.213
It's nothing to be concerned
about.

13:59.213 --> 14:00.590
It's within grinding.

14:00.590 --> 14:02.675
- It is so clean
in its lines.

14:02.675 --> 14:05.720
I don't see any issues at all
with the steel.

14:05.720 --> 14:06.804
It's beautiful work.

14:06.804 --> 14:08.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:08.514 --> 14:10.850
- All right, let's move on
to Doran's blade.

14:10.850 --> 14:13.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:13.811 --> 14:16.439
- I'd like to see him
take a lot of this weight out.

14:16.439 --> 14:19.067
I mean, it's just too obtuse
to do some of our testing,

14:19.067 --> 14:22.737
and it's not what I would
consider a classic dirk shape.

14:22.737 --> 14:24.697
- It'll cut some apples
like an axe would,

14:24.697 --> 14:26.616
unless I go do something
to that knife of mine.

14:26.616 --> 14:29.285
- If he could actually
grind that down

14:29.285 --> 14:31.204
and start to create
a dirk tip on this,

14:31.204 --> 14:32.914
and lose some of that belly,

14:32.914 --> 14:34.415
you would have
that classic shape.

14:34.415 --> 14:36.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:36.209 --> 14:38.377
- This is Johnathan's blade.

14:38.377 --> 14:39.962
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:39.962 --> 14:41.756
<i>- More classic dirk shape.</i>

14:41.756 --> 14:43.966
Instead of 1/3 and 1/3,
he's got 1/2 and 1/2.

14:43.966 --> 14:46.010
There are surface
spider web cracks.

14:46.010 --> 14:47.386
They don't seem critical,

14:47.386 --> 14:49.180
and they probably
will grind out.

14:49.180 --> 14:50.848
- Johnathan was awesome
about his file work.

14:50.848 --> 14:52.975
It was very clever,
just to use the grinder.

14:52.975 --> 14:56.020
- The blade itself is straight.
It's a nice-looking piece.

14:56.020 --> 14:58.064
- The thing I don't like
about it is the fact

14:58.064 --> 14:59.565
that he's got a--

14:59.565 --> 15:01.776
a bumped-in ricasso right here.

15:01.776 --> 15:02.944
<i>It's a great foundation.</i>

15:02.944 --> 15:04.904
It needs refining.

15:04.904 --> 15:06.155
<i>- All right, gents.</i>

15:06.155 --> 15:07.615
Doug, have you made

15:07.615 --> 15:08.699
your decision?
- Yes, I have.

15:08.699 --> 15:09.659
- Dave?
- Yeah.

15:09.659 --> 15:10.910
- Ben?
- Yes.

15:10.910 --> 15:13.287
- Let's go tell our smiths.

15:13.287 --> 15:14.497
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:14.497 --> 15:16.082
Bladesmiths,

15:16.082 --> 15:17.583
the judges' deliberation
is complete,

15:17.583 --> 15:20.128
and they have made
a final decision.

15:20.128 --> 15:22.380
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge is...

15:22.380 --> 15:27.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.093 --> 15:29.011
Ben, your blade
didn't make the cut.

15:29.011 --> 15:31.597
Doug Marcaida's
gonna tell you why.

15:31.597 --> 15:33.057
- Ben, we really liked the look

15:33.057 --> 15:34.433
and design of your dirk,

15:34.433 --> 15:36.102
but you developed cracks

15:36.102 --> 15:38.396
at critical junctures
of your blade.

15:38.396 --> 15:39.939
<i>You had cracks in your spine,</i>

15:39.939 --> 15:41.524
<i>you had cracks on your tang</i>

15:41.524 --> 15:43.317
<i>that went all the way through,</i>

15:43.317 --> 15:44.318
and we just feel that you will

15:44.318 --> 15:45.903
not be able to fix that.

15:45.903 --> 15:47.321
For this reason,
we're sending you home.

15:47.321 --> 15:49.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.031 --> 15:50.658
- Ben, please,
surrender your blade.

15:50.658 --> 15:53.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:53.161 --> 15:54.996
<i>- I'm absolutely devastated</i>
<i>that I'm not moving on</i>

15:54.996 --> 15:56.455
<i>to the next round.</i>
Thank you.

15:56.455 --> 15:58.166
I came out here to prove

15:58.166 --> 15:59.500
that I was a great bladesmith.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.377
<i>I worked hard,</i>

16:01.377 --> 16:02.920
<i>I did everything</i>
<i>I felt like I needed to do,</i>

16:02.920 --> 16:05.173
but I never mess with 52100,

16:05.173 --> 16:07.550
and it is a bitch. [laughs]

16:07.550 --> 16:10.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:10.845 --> 16:12.388
- Gentlemen, congratulations.

16:12.388 --> 16:13.514
You've made it
to the second round

16:13.514 --> 16:14.640
of this competition.

16:14.640 --> 16:16.392
All you have to do now

16:16.392 --> 16:18.352
is attach handles
to your blades,

16:18.352 --> 16:20.062
turning them into
fully-functional

16:20.062 --> 16:21.981
Scottish dirks.

16:21.981 --> 16:23.649
<i>We'd also like to see</i>
<i>a brass guard</i>

16:23.649 --> 16:26.819
<i>and pommel cap</i>
<i>on your blades.</i>

16:26.819 --> 16:28.779
You will have three hours
in this round.

16:28.779 --> 16:30.281
When the time runs out,

16:30.281 --> 16:31.782
each of your weapons
will be tested

16:31.782 --> 16:33.242
for strength and durability

16:33.242 --> 16:35.494
in an oil drum stab,

16:35.494 --> 16:38.915
and for sharpness
in an apple slice.

16:38.915 --> 16:40.291
Good luck, bladesmiths.

16:40.291 --> 16:42.126
Your three hours starts...
now.

16:42.126 --> 16:43.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:43.920 --> 16:46.422
Who's got the most work
to do here, Ben?

16:46.422 --> 16:49.342
- Doran, 'cause he's got
a really fat blade,

16:49.342 --> 16:51.135
and he needs to work
on that profile.

16:51.135 --> 16:53.471
- But what about
the offset tang

16:53.471 --> 16:55.890
that is on Johnathan's blade
right now?

16:55.890 --> 16:58.517
- There's a lot of material
there he can just grind away,

16:58.517 --> 17:00.269
and once he gets it
thinned out a bit,

17:00.269 --> 17:01.938
he can just straighten it
with the torch.

17:01.938 --> 17:04.023
<i>- Before I even</i>
<i>start the handle,</i>

17:04.023 --> 17:05.858
<i>my tang needs to be</i>
<i>straightened out.</i>

17:05.858 --> 17:07.735
Damn it.

17:07.735 --> 17:09.612
I hadn't had to light
an oxyacetylene torch

17:09.612 --> 17:11.405
since I was in high school,

17:11.405 --> 17:12.949
and that was obviously
a very long time ago.

17:12.949 --> 17:15.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:15.326 --> 17:18.663
It will not cooperate.

17:18.663 --> 17:19.664
- He wasn't running
the acetylene

17:19.664 --> 17:21.249
at a high enough rate,

17:21.249 --> 17:22.416
so every time
he turned the oxygen on,

17:22.416 --> 17:24.126
it was blowing the flame out.

17:24.126 --> 17:26.545
- Gotta do it the hard way.

17:26.545 --> 17:28.422
I'm just gonna draw
the hardness back

17:28.422 --> 17:30.716
with a MAPP gas torch.

17:30.716 --> 17:32.760
Tick, tock, tick, tock,
tick, tock.

17:32.760 --> 17:34.637
- That torch is too small
for this job.

17:34.637 --> 17:37.807
This is just a waste of time.

17:37.807 --> 17:40.226
- I see Doran going to
the belt over there

17:40.226 --> 17:42.144
with a grinder.
He's been working on that tip.

17:42.144 --> 17:43.938
Hopefully, he re-profiles it--

17:43.938 --> 17:45.940
made more dirk-ish like.

17:45.940 --> 17:48.276
- That would be a very smart
move on his part.

17:48.276 --> 17:51.529
<i>- The most crucial thing</i>
<i>to get right in round two</i>

17:51.529 --> 17:54.240
is make a dirk
out of this thing.

17:54.240 --> 17:55.533
Honestly,
I'm gonna win this thing,

17:55.533 --> 17:57.743
whether it kills me or not.

17:57.743 --> 18:00.371
<i>- I'm taking very careful</i>
<i>measurements</i>

18:00.371 --> 18:02.456
because I have a plan
in my head

18:02.456 --> 18:04.834
about how this is
supposed to go together.

18:04.834 --> 18:06.168
What I have to do
to this knife

18:06.168 --> 18:07.753
is refine the shape,

18:07.753 --> 18:08.879
remove a fair amount of metal

18:08.879 --> 18:10.256
so I have a decent edge,

18:10.256 --> 18:12.466
in a very short period of time.

18:12.466 --> 18:14.468
- Man, I like
watching Phil work.

18:14.468 --> 18:16.095
He knows exactly
what he's doing

18:16.095 --> 18:17.888
and every place he's going.
- Yeah.

18:17.888 --> 18:19.515
- [laughs]

18:19.515 --> 18:20.975
Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

18:20.975 --> 18:22.602
You have two hours remaining

18:22.602 --> 18:24.312
to finish your work.

18:24.312 --> 18:26.772
- It's time to
get the guard on.

18:26.772 --> 18:29.817
<i>It always takes a while</i>
<i>to fit a brass guard.</i>

18:29.817 --> 18:31.193
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.193 --> 18:33.070
<i>I am filing and filing</i>

18:33.070 --> 18:34.739
<i>and test fit</i>
<i>and file and file and file</i>

18:34.739 --> 18:36.324
<i>and test fit,</i>
<i>file and file and file.</i>

18:36.324 --> 18:37.825
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:37.825 --> 18:39.201
It is what it is.

18:39.201 --> 18:41.162
<i>Everything takes time,</i>

18:41.162 --> 18:43.247
and time we ain't got.

18:43.247 --> 18:45.041
- You see a lot
of different designs,

18:45.041 --> 18:47.043
especially in the handles,
on dirks.

18:47.043 --> 18:49.629
Typically, it's very similar
to the Scottish thistle,

18:49.629 --> 18:51.005
but there's a type of dirk

18:51.005 --> 18:52.715
that has a very,
very short handle.

18:52.715 --> 18:54.133
It's literally only
the size of your palm,

18:54.133 --> 18:55.968
and it's very cylindrical,

18:55.968 --> 18:57.720
and often those were held
in the targe handle

18:57.720 --> 18:59.805
so that blade
was behind your shield.

18:59.805 --> 19:01.515
Someone gets up close, boom!

19:01.515 --> 19:03.225
Down in the thigh,
into the gut.

19:03.225 --> 19:04.268
- Ew.

19:04.268 --> 19:06.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:06.145 --> 19:07.605
- Now, look at Doran.

19:07.605 --> 19:09.065
He's picked
his handle material,

19:09.065 --> 19:10.483
but he split it in half.
Do you think

19:10.483 --> 19:11.984
he's gonna frame it
together?

19:11.984 --> 19:13.819
- I think he's going to do
a frame tang.

19:13.819 --> 19:15.237
<i>- I've never seen anybody</i>
<i>make handles</i>

19:15.237 --> 19:17.114
quite like I do.

19:17.114 --> 19:19.283
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>the technique I use,</i>

19:19.283 --> 19:23.204
because nobody's taught me.
I just go. I do.

19:23.204 --> 19:24.789
- I hope his time management

19:24.789 --> 19:26.666
is gonna bear this all out.

19:26.666 --> 19:29.627
- He needs to really
refine that blade shape.

19:29.627 --> 19:31.545
<i>- I've seen</i>
<i>too many bladesmiths</i>

19:31.545 --> 19:32.963
make crappy handles.

19:32.963 --> 19:34.840
<i>If you can't swing the knife,</i>

19:34.840 --> 19:36.634
it doesn't matter how good
the edge that I make is.

19:36.634 --> 19:39.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:39.261 --> 19:41.514
- I'm looking for something
like a rosewood.

19:41.514 --> 19:43.140
<i>The warmth of the brass</i>

19:43.140 --> 19:44.433
<i>and the warmth of the rosewood</i>

19:44.433 --> 19:46.769
go really well together.

19:46.769 --> 19:48.688
- Is Phil gonna do
a burn-through?

19:48.688 --> 19:51.399
- Oh, I've seen this go wrong
so many times.

19:51.399 --> 19:52.733
- Yeah.

19:52.733 --> 19:54.568
- I'm gonna do a burn-through,

19:54.568 --> 19:56.278
because I've found
it gives the best results,

19:56.278 --> 19:58.280
<i>and it's the fastest.</i>

19:58.280 --> 20:00.700
Right now,
those 50 years of experience

20:00.700 --> 20:02.243
are really coming in handy.

20:02.243 --> 20:03.911
- It looks like
Phil has done this

20:03.911 --> 20:05.705
a hundred times.

20:05.705 --> 20:08.249
It's like it's going
really smoothly for him.

20:08.249 --> 20:10.668
<i>- I have never had a problem</i>
<i>with burn-through.</i>

20:10.668 --> 20:12.878
<i>It has always worked for me.</i>

20:12.878 --> 20:14.422
- Bladesmiths!

20:14.422 --> 20:16.716
Two hours has elapsed!

20:16.716 --> 20:19.468
- Desert ironwood
is tough wood.

20:19.468 --> 20:21.095
Scottish weapons like the dirk

20:21.095 --> 20:23.514
generally have black wood
or a blackened,

20:23.514 --> 20:25.599
<i>thistle-shaped handle.</i>

20:25.599 --> 20:28.227
<i>I've got the guard on,</i>
<i>I've got the pommel cap,</i>

20:28.227 --> 20:30.646
<i>I've got the brass nut</i>
<i>with the pin in it,</i>

20:30.646 --> 20:32.440
<i>but I've always been</i>

20:32.440 --> 20:34.692
a belt-and-suspenders
kind of guy,

20:34.692 --> 20:37.403
<i>so it wouldn't hurt to have</i>
<i>a pin for the handle, too,</i>

20:37.403 --> 20:39.280
because you never know

20:39.280 --> 20:41.157
when something on a nut
could fail,

20:41.157 --> 20:43.367
and you don't need
flying, sharp objects

20:43.367 --> 20:45.077
in unintended areas.

20:45.077 --> 20:46.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:46.579 --> 20:47.788
- Uh-oh.

20:47.788 --> 20:49.457
What's happening over here?

20:49.457 --> 20:51.709
- It's a fun game
of "find that tang."

20:51.709 --> 20:54.420
Pray you don't blow out
the other side.

20:54.420 --> 20:56.088
<i>- This was a bad idea.</i>

20:56.088 --> 20:57.840
<i>If my tang breaks,</i>

20:57.840 --> 20:59.592
I'm gonna be pretty disgusted
with myself.

20:59.592 --> 21:01.177
- Don't force it, man.

21:01.177 --> 21:03.095
- I'm obviously nervous.

21:03.095 --> 21:04.805
<i>$10,000 riding on this.</i>

21:04.805 --> 21:05.870
- Oh, boy.

21:08.350 --> 21:11.520
- Not this time--
just make that pin decorative.

21:11.520 --> 21:13.981
<i>- I went a decent way</i>
<i>into the tang.</i>

21:13.981 --> 21:16.859
Sometimes the squeeze
ain't worth the juice.

21:20.571 --> 21:22.615
- Doran is a wizard
with that grinder, man.

21:22.615 --> 21:24.116
He was first in his class

21:24.116 --> 21:25.409
at real school
of handle-making.

21:25.409 --> 21:27.286
- There you go.

21:27.286 --> 21:28.746
- A lot of Scottish dirks
have a checker pattern.

21:28.746 --> 21:30.581
I tried to match that
checker pattern.

21:30.581 --> 21:32.082
<i>I came close.</i>
<i>It's pretty,</i>

21:32.082 --> 21:33.459
<i>but it's not symmetrical,</i>

21:33.459 --> 21:35.252
but, you know, neither am I.

21:35.252 --> 21:36.462
- I think at this point,
he's just going for

21:36.462 --> 21:37.838
some points for style.

21:37.838 --> 21:39.215
I mean, I would like
to see him

21:39.215 --> 21:41.842
put a serious edge on it.

21:41.842 --> 21:43.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:43.302 --> 21:46.222
<i>- I have my pommel guard on</i>

21:46.222 --> 21:49.016
and I will get this handle made
in 30 minutes.

21:49.016 --> 21:50.476
- He drew out the shape

21:50.476 --> 21:53.103
of what that handle's
supposed to be.

21:53.103 --> 21:55.231
Those are great guidelines.

21:55.231 --> 21:57.858
- The only thing I'm nervous
about Phil for is time.

21:57.858 --> 21:59.485
- Oh, Phil, abandon that saw

21:59.485 --> 22:01.403
and get to a grinder,
my friend.

22:01.403 --> 22:02.947
<i>- I'm actually very pleased</i>

22:02.947 --> 22:04.615
with the way things
are coming along.

22:04.615 --> 22:06.283
That band saw
really speeded things up.

22:06.283 --> 22:07.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:07.701 --> 22:09.578
- Ten seconds!

22:09.578 --> 22:13.249
Eight, seven, six, five,

22:13.249 --> 22:17.378
four, three, two, one.

22:17.378 --> 22:19.338
Bladesmiths,
drop your tools.

22:19.338 --> 22:20.923
This round is over.

22:20.923 --> 22:22.967
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:22.967 --> 22:24.802
<i>- That is the ugliest handle</i>
<i>I've ever made,</i>

22:24.802 --> 22:27.263
<i>but it is ridiculously sharp,</i>

22:27.263 --> 22:30.015
<i>and it looks pretty good</i>
<i>from about eight feet away,</i>

22:30.015 --> 22:33.769
if you don't have
really good eyesight.

22:33.769 --> 22:35.771
- Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

22:35.771 --> 22:37.690
I'm gonna be taking
each of your dirks

22:37.690 --> 22:39.233
and testing them
by hammering them,

22:39.233 --> 22:41.402
six times each,
into this oil can.

22:41.402 --> 22:42.695
Remember, this test
is all about

22:42.695 --> 22:43.946
what happens to the dirks.

22:43.946 --> 22:44.989
Phil, you're up first.

22:44.989 --> 22:46.073
You ready?

22:46.073 --> 22:47.074
- Yes, sir.

22:47.074 --> 22:49.368
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:49.368 --> 22:51.871
<i>I'm feeling nervous, because</i>
<i>when I see the oil drum</i>

22:51.871 --> 22:53.372
<i>for the first time,</i>
<i>I'm thinking,</i>

22:53.372 --> 22:54.665
"Well, that could break
that point."

22:54.665 --> 23:01.463
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:05.175 --> 23:06.385
- No respect
for that barrel.

23:06.385 --> 23:08.345
- Mm-mmm. That poor barrel.

23:08.345 --> 23:15.477
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:15.477 --> 23:17.813
- Well, Phil,
held up pretty well.

23:17.813 --> 23:19.690
Little bit of rolling
at the edge here.

23:19.690 --> 23:21.775
<i>Minor, but still there.</i>

23:21.775 --> 23:23.235
In all,

23:23.235 --> 23:24.570
the dirk held up very well.

23:24.570 --> 23:25.988
- Good job, man.

23:25.988 --> 23:27.615
- Doran, you're up next.
You ready?

23:27.615 --> 23:28.574
- Kill that thing!

23:28.574 --> 23:29.617
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:29.617 --> 23:31.577
<i>I am nervous.</i>

23:31.577 --> 23:33.037
<i>I might've spent too much time</i>
<i>on my handle,</i>

23:33.037 --> 23:35.205
and not enough time
on my blade,

23:35.205 --> 23:37.625
<i>and I don't know if,</i>
<i>when he smacks that blade,</i>

23:37.625 --> 23:39.251
if it's just gonna
wreck my tip,

23:39.251 --> 23:41.211
'cause I've got a point
on there.

23:41.211 --> 23:48.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:52.014 --> 23:53.849
Die.

23:53.849 --> 24:01.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:01.065 --> 24:03.484
- Well, Doran,
you still have a dirk.

24:03.484 --> 24:05.235
It's not razor-sharp anymore,

24:05.235 --> 24:06.904
Down here, there's just
a little rolling,

24:06.904 --> 24:09.490
but the handle
is relatively small for a dirk,

24:09.490 --> 24:11.825
but comfortable.

24:11.825 --> 24:12.952
Overall, very well done.

24:12.952 --> 24:14.411
- Thank you, sir.

24:14.411 --> 24:17.331
- Johnathan, you're up.
- Ready.

24:17.331 --> 24:20.250
<i>I'm a little worried, because</i>
<i>you can crack the blade,</i>

24:20.250 --> 24:21.835
you can dull the blade,
you can drive the blade

24:21.835 --> 24:23.295
<i>clean out of the handle.</i>

24:23.295 --> 24:24.755
Anything can go wrong.

24:24.755 --> 24:31.679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:37.351 --> 24:39.895
Came out a lot easier
than I expected.

24:39.895 --> 24:41.939
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:41.939 --> 24:43.565
- Well, Johnathan,
in all,

24:43.565 --> 24:45.192
it held up well,
but the handle

24:45.192 --> 24:47.486
is a little sharp
towards the front.

24:47.486 --> 24:49.029
It's not quite as comfortable
to grip

24:49.029 --> 24:50.406
as some of the others,

24:50.406 --> 24:52.449
but I like the--
your choice of wood.

24:52.449 --> 24:53.951
In total,

24:53.951 --> 24:55.369
it's still a fighting knife.
Well done.

24:55.369 --> 24:57.413
- Thank you.

24:57.413 --> 24:59.498
- All right, gentlemen.
Next up is the sharpness test.

24:59.498 --> 25:01.625
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

25:01.625 --> 25:03.377
what your knives do
to these apples.

25:03.377 --> 25:05.921
A sharp edge should give me
a good, clean cut

25:05.921 --> 25:07.589
straight through those apples.
A dull edge--

25:07.589 --> 25:09.299
well, we can see
the apples crack,

25:09.299 --> 25:11.218
or you can see the skin torn.

25:11.218 --> 25:12.970
Phil, you're up first.
You ready?

25:12.970 --> 25:13.887
- Yes, sir.

25:13.887 --> 25:20.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:25.524 --> 25:27.359
- Good job.
- Yeah.

25:27.359 --> 25:28.694
- All right, Phil.

25:28.694 --> 25:30.070
Right off the bat,

25:30.070 --> 25:31.363
I love the profile
of your knife,

25:31.363 --> 25:32.990
that classic shape.

25:32.990 --> 25:34.700
It cut cleanly
through these apples,

25:34.700 --> 25:36.201
but right at the edge,

25:36.201 --> 25:38.537
you can see these
little flaps of skin.

25:38.537 --> 25:40.539
There's one section
on this knife

25:40.539 --> 25:42.249
where it took that roll.

25:42.249 --> 25:44.126
Definitely a sharp knife,
though, a good cutter.

25:44.126 --> 25:45.210
Nicely done.

25:45.210 --> 25:46.503
- Thank you, sir.

25:46.503 --> 25:47.880
- Doran, you're up.
You ready?

25:47.880 --> 25:50.090
- Oh, kill those
poor little guys.

25:50.090 --> 25:52.217
<i>My blades are hackers</i>
<i>and stabbers.</i>

25:52.217 --> 25:54.470
You know?
There's slashers in there,

25:54.470 --> 25:56.513
but I'm not real confident

25:56.513 --> 25:58.182
<i>that I have a sharp edge</i>
<i>on that thing.</i>

25:59.475 --> 26:06.482
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:11.653 --> 26:13.489
- Your blade does have an edge,

26:13.489 --> 26:15.240
and it will cut,

26:15.240 --> 26:19.244
but that one inch
by 3/8 of an inch is a wedge.

26:19.244 --> 26:22.122
This first apple--
it's got a cut to about here,

26:22.122 --> 26:23.957
and then the rest of this
is actually broken.

26:23.957 --> 26:25.084
For a slicing blade,

26:25.084 --> 26:27.002
it just--it's fighting.

26:27.002 --> 26:29.546
For a chop,
it's gonna do a lot of damage,

26:29.546 --> 26:33.133
but for this test,
that wedge shape

26:33.133 --> 26:35.344
is just not gonna pass through
those apples very well.

26:35.344 --> 26:36.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:36.553 --> 26:38.180
All right, Johnathan.

26:38.180 --> 26:40.140
You're up.
- Let's do it.

26:40.140 --> 26:41.767
<i>My blade suffered</i>
<i>the worst damage</i>

26:41.767 --> 26:43.602
<i>in the barrel stab.</i>

26:43.602 --> 26:46.772
It has the least-finished
handle on the floor.

26:46.772 --> 26:48.774
<i>Anything could send me home</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

26:48.774 --> 26:53.612
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:53.612 --> 26:55.447
- Nice.

26:55.447 --> 26:58.867
- First-off, you've got
a big convex edge to this,

26:58.867 --> 27:00.577
which cut really nicely,

27:00.577 --> 27:03.664
but there are a couple of
small rolls,

27:03.664 --> 27:07.126
and your handle,
though shaped nicely this way,

27:07.126 --> 27:09.086
is very lean here.

27:09.086 --> 27:11.255
But it's definitely a cutter.
Nicely done.

27:11.255 --> 27:12.297
- Thank you.

27:12.297 --> 27:14.925
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:14.925 --> 27:17.177
- Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete

27:17.177 --> 27:19.221
and they've made
their final decision.

27:19.221 --> 27:21.557
The bladesmith
leaving the forge is...

27:21.557 --> 27:26.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:26.228 --> 27:28.772
Doran, your blade
did not make the cut.

27:28.772 --> 27:31.316
David Baker's
gonna tell you why.

27:31.316 --> 27:33.151
- Doran, you made
a solid knife there,

27:33.151 --> 27:34.653
and I really appreciate
the fact that

27:34.653 --> 27:37.322
you listened and re-profiled
that tip,

27:37.322 --> 27:39.950
but in the slice test
and the sharpness test,

27:39.950 --> 27:42.244
your blade
with that wedge profile

27:42.244 --> 27:43.829
just didn't cut.

27:43.829 --> 27:45.956
That's why
we're letting you go.

27:45.956 --> 27:48.000
- Doran, please surrender
your weapon.

27:48.000 --> 27:49.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:49.418 --> 27:51.336
<i>- I'm not upset that I lost,</i>

27:51.336 --> 27:52.379
<i>or I didn't get to</i>
<i>where I needed to be</i>

27:52.379 --> 27:53.505
<i>in this competition.</i>

27:53.505 --> 27:54.590
These are tears of joy.

27:54.590 --> 27:55.549
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:55.549 --> 27:57.509
This is happy.

27:57.509 --> 27:58.677
<i>I just lived out a dream,</i>

27:58.677 --> 28:00.220
<i>and with somebody who's--</i>

28:00.220 --> 28:03.098
live in a little town,
like I do...

28:03.098 --> 28:04.600
<i>This is worth more than gold.</i>

28:04.600 --> 28:08.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:08.729 --> 28:10.814
- Phil, Johnathan,
congratulations.

28:10.814 --> 28:13.150
You've made it to the final
round of this competition,

28:13.150 --> 28:14.651
which means that you're both
one step closer

28:14.651 --> 28:16.320
to that title and that check.

28:16.320 --> 28:17.863
All you have to do now

28:17.863 --> 28:19.615
is defeat the man
standing next to you

28:19.615 --> 28:22.159
by re-creating
an iconic weapon from history.

28:22.159 --> 28:23.952
That weapon is...

28:23.952 --> 28:25.913
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:25.913 --> 28:27.456
The German halberd.

28:27.456 --> 28:29.917
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:29.917 --> 28:32.461
<i>Used by Swiss armies</i>
<i>during the medieval era,</i>

28:32.461 --> 28:35.422
<i>the halberd was a versatile</i>
<i>and lethal weapon of war.</i>

28:35.422 --> 28:37.007
<i>A combination of spike,</i>
<i>hook, and axe,</i>

28:37.007 --> 28:38.759
<i>it was a triple threat.</i>

28:38.759 --> 28:40.844
<i>Foot soldiers</i>
<i>would defend themselves</i>

28:40.844 --> 28:42.554
<i>against knights on horseback</i>
<i>by using its back hook</i>

28:42.554 --> 28:44.139
<i>to catch and dismount</i>
<i>their opponents,</i>

28:44.139 --> 28:45.766
<i>and then move in for the kill,</i>

28:45.766 --> 28:47.684
<i>using the spear point</i>
<i>to thrust,</i>

28:47.684 --> 28:49.686
<i>or the axe to slice</i>
<i>through armor.</i>

28:49.686 --> 28:51.605
<i>An infamous killer,</i>
<i>King Charles the Bold,</i>

28:51.605 --> 28:53.273
<i>the Duke of Burgundy,</i>
<i>met his fate</i>

28:53.273 --> 28:55.192
<i>when his head</i>
<i>was halved by a halberd,</i>

28:55.192 --> 28:58.070
<i>ending the Burgundian Wars</i>
<i>in 1477.</i>

28:58.070 --> 29:00.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:00.280 --> 29:02.407
Your halberd's head
must include a spike,

29:02.407 --> 29:05.202
a hook,
and an axe head.

29:05.202 --> 29:07.079
The length of the shaft
of your halberd

29:07.079 --> 29:09.539
must be six feet
from the end

29:09.539 --> 29:10.958
to the center junction.

29:10.958 --> 29:13.210
Bladesmiths,
that's a lot of work,

29:13.210 --> 29:14.711
and you only have five days

29:14.711 --> 29:16.630
in which to get it done.

29:16.630 --> 29:18.507
At the end of five days,
you'll return and present

29:18.507 --> 29:20.717
your German halberds
to our panel of expert judges,

29:20.717 --> 29:23.929
and only after they've
brutally tested these things

29:23.929 --> 29:26.139
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:26.139 --> 29:27.557
and hand you a check
for ten grand.

29:27.557 --> 29:28.558
How's that sound?

29:28.558 --> 29:30.018
- Walk in the park.

29:30.018 --> 29:31.520
[laughter]

29:31.520 --> 29:33.188
- All right, bladesmiths,
good luck.

29:33.188 --> 29:34.523
We'll see you in five days.

29:34.523 --> 29:38.485
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:38.485 --> 29:41.071
[metallic clanging]

29:41.071 --> 29:43.740
<i>- This particular halberd</i>
<i>has an axe on one side,</i>

29:43.740 --> 29:46.243
a hook on the other side,
a spike.

29:46.243 --> 29:49.037
<i>The bottom fits into</i>
<i>a wood shaft.</i>

29:49.037 --> 29:51.832
The originals were not
forged in one piece,

29:51.832 --> 29:54.584
<i>and that's the approach</i>
<i>that I'm going to take.</i>

29:54.584 --> 29:57.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:57.713 --> 30:00.132
<i>The most challenging element</i>
<i>is going to be</i>

30:00.132 --> 30:02.175
making the central cross.

30:02.175 --> 30:04.386
<i>It's a very compact forging.</i>

30:04.386 --> 30:08.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:08.098 --> 30:10.100
<i>Really, it would be easier</i>
<i>to just fabricate it</i>

30:10.100 --> 30:12.644
<i>to get something that looks</i>
<i>okay at 200 yards,</i>

30:12.644 --> 30:15.564
but this show is not
"Fabricated in Fire."

30:15.564 --> 30:17.315
It's "Forged in Fire."

30:17.315 --> 30:20.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:20.902 --> 30:22.529
<i>Aside from tired,</i>

30:22.529 --> 30:23.739
<i>at the end of the day,</i>

30:23.739 --> 30:25.407
I accomplished quite a bit.

30:25.407 --> 30:27.159
<i>Nothing blew up in my face.</i>

30:27.159 --> 30:28.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:28.201 --> 30:30.162
That's pretty good.

30:30.162 --> 30:32.164
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:32.164 --> 30:33.957
- Not feeling
top of my game right now.

30:33.957 --> 30:35.250
[coughs]

30:35.250 --> 30:38.462
I am making a halberd.

30:38.462 --> 30:40.756
Knock it down enough
to get it in the fly press,

30:40.756 --> 30:43.633
I gonna start drawing out
the spear head.

30:43.633 --> 30:45.927
The steel is not moving
worth a damn.

30:45.927 --> 30:47.387
I swear, that thing
gets heavier

30:47.387 --> 30:48.805
every time I pick it up.

30:48.805 --> 30:49.931
[exhales heavily]

30:49.931 --> 30:51.224
I am feeling like crap.

30:51.224 --> 30:52.392
[sniffs]

30:52.392 --> 30:53.894
My nose is stopped up.

30:53.894 --> 30:55.729
[coughs]

30:55.729 --> 30:57.105
The more I cough,
the more I have

30:57.105 --> 30:58.815
to hold back puking.

30:58.815 --> 31:00.776
[coughs]

31:00.776 --> 31:02.527
I don't want to puke.

31:02.527 --> 31:04.988
<i>I really wanted to have</i>
<i>the shoulder down</i>

31:04.988 --> 31:07.574
started for the socket
by the end of today,

31:07.574 --> 31:09.743
but I'm just running
out of gas.

31:09.743 --> 31:11.536
<i>Tomorrow's gonna be about</i>
<i>a lot of caffeine</i>

31:11.536 --> 31:13.872
and cold medicine
and heat, beat, and repeat.

31:13.872 --> 31:16.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:16.333 --> 31:18.168
- Yesterday,
I was able to accomplish

31:18.168 --> 31:19.544
forging the core element.

31:19.544 --> 31:21.463
<i>Today, I need to continue</i>

31:21.463 --> 31:22.964
<i>to shape the other elements</i>

31:22.964 --> 31:25.175
<i>and attach them to the core.</i>

31:25.175 --> 31:27.427
<i>It is a tricky</i>
<i>shaping problem.</i>

31:27.427 --> 31:29.846
<i>I'm drawing on</i>
<i>everything I know.</i>

31:29.846 --> 31:33.308
I'm no professional
halberd maker, that's for sure.

31:33.308 --> 31:37.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:37.479 --> 31:39.106
<i>It's almost done.</i>
<i>The problem is,</i>

31:39.106 --> 31:40.565
it's just too thick.

31:40.565 --> 31:42.359
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:42.359 --> 31:44.236
<i>Where I want it to be</i>

31:44.236 --> 31:46.196
was to have the--
all the parts into one piece,

31:46.196 --> 31:47.948
and I didn't get that,

31:47.948 --> 31:49.699
<i>because I did spend</i>
<i>a lot of time</i>

31:49.699 --> 31:51.201
<i>on the design.</i>

31:51.201 --> 31:52.911
So, bye.

31:52.911 --> 31:54.371
Good night.

31:55.831 --> 31:57.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:57.666 --> 32:01.086
- Still feeling
like death today. [coughs]

32:01.086 --> 32:02.254
<i>It's an uphill battle.</i>

32:02.254 --> 32:03.296
Come on.

32:03.296 --> 32:04.506
<i>It's a fight.</i>

32:04.506 --> 32:06.508
Back in the fire. [grunts]

32:06.508 --> 32:08.343
<i>It's not an easy piece</i>
<i>to make,</i>

32:08.343 --> 32:10.887
<i>but even with</i>
<i>the way I'm feeling,</i>

32:10.887 --> 32:12.597
my daddy didn't raise
no quitters.

32:12.597 --> 32:14.683
[coughs]

32:14.683 --> 32:16.726
<i>But I'm definitely</i>
<i>feeling stressed</i>

32:16.726 --> 32:17.727
<i>about my timeline.</i>

32:17.727 --> 32:19.354
[coughs]

32:19.354 --> 32:21.481
I need to stretch out
the axe blade,

32:21.481 --> 32:22.816
<i>form the axe blade,</i>

32:22.816 --> 32:24.359
<i>form out the hook,</i>

32:24.359 --> 32:25.402
<i>draw out the spear head,</i>

32:25.402 --> 32:27.070
<i>form a socket,</i>

32:27.070 --> 32:28.196
and then clean
this horrible mess up.

32:28.196 --> 32:30.115
<i>That is a lot on my plate.</i>

32:30.115 --> 32:32.784
<i>I'm worried about</i>
<i>getting the weapon done.</i>

32:34.995 --> 32:37.122
<i>♪ ♪</i>
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:37.122 --> 32:39.791
- I'm feeling tan,
rested, and ready. [laughs]

32:39.791 --> 32:42.085
<i>Today, I'm going to do the</i>

32:42.085 --> 32:43.753
<i>post-heat treatment</i>
<i>and grinding.</i>

32:43.753 --> 32:46.423
My halberd will be
fairly light, wieldy...

32:46.423 --> 32:47.966
I need water.

32:47.966 --> 32:50.844
And it will be
sharp and strong.

32:50.844 --> 32:52.721
<i>Sharpening the blades</i>

32:52.721 --> 32:55.056
<i>took a lot longer</i>
<i>than I thought it would.</i>

32:55.056 --> 32:56.975
There was a lot more metal
in the edge

32:56.975 --> 32:59.060
<i>than it looked like.</i>

32:59.060 --> 33:01.897
I'll let the judges
do their worst.

33:01.897 --> 33:03.815
It's the end of day four,

33:03.815 --> 33:05.275
and all my metal parts
are ready for assembling.

33:05.275 --> 33:07.402
<i>I'm really happy</i>
<i>with everything.</i>

33:07.402 --> 33:12.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:12.490 --> 33:15.035
<i>- I am between an inch</i>
<i>and a 1/2 inch away</i>

33:15.035 --> 33:17.245
<i>from being able to pull</i>
<i>the axe head far enough</i>

33:17.245 --> 33:18.663
<i>away from the center line.</i>

33:18.663 --> 33:21.166
[loud clattering]
Oh...

33:21.166 --> 33:23.001
<i>And it's just gonna be</i>
<i>what it is.</i>

33:23.001 --> 33:25.587
The piece won't even fit
in the propane forge anymore,

33:25.587 --> 33:27.214
so it's gonna be cold
from here out.

33:27.214 --> 33:29.758
All that ugly yellow smoke
you see in there?

33:29.758 --> 33:31.968
That's sulfur burning
out of the coal.

33:31.968 --> 33:33.386
If I can move that

33:33.386 --> 33:34.971
all the way in line with this,

33:34.971 --> 33:36.097
I may have enough room
right there.

33:36.097 --> 33:39.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:39.017 --> 33:40.310
Still like a 1/2 inch.

33:40.310 --> 33:41.603
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:41.603 --> 33:43.104
That is a wasp.

33:43.104 --> 33:45.106
Hate wasps.

33:45.106 --> 33:46.858
They don't make honey.

33:46.858 --> 33:48.360
They don't die
after they sting you.

33:48.360 --> 33:50.779
Their entire job
is to be [bleep].

33:50.779 --> 33:52.489
[bleep] you.

33:52.489 --> 33:54.783
Today was, by far,
the hardest day.

33:54.783 --> 33:57.118
<i>I was outside in the heat.</i>

33:57.118 --> 33:59.955
<i>The hammering that I did</i>
<i>was all by hand.</i>

33:59.955 --> 34:02.749
<i>The grinding that I did</i>
<i>was all with an angle grinder.</i>

34:02.749 --> 34:04.668
I feel like crap.

34:04.668 --> 34:08.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:08.213 --> 34:10.590
- Phil, Johnathan,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:10.590 --> 34:12.467
Phil, how'd it go for you?

34:12.467 --> 34:14.052
- Well, it went pretty well,
and I'm still alive.

34:14.052 --> 34:15.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:15.553 --> 34:18.181
The blade has 1095 edges on it

34:18.181 --> 34:20.183
<i>welded to mild steel.</i>

34:20.183 --> 34:22.060
<i>I put on a ferrule.</i>

34:22.060 --> 34:23.061
<i>That was the fun part</i>
<i>of the piece.</i>

34:23.061 --> 34:24.562
- Johnathan, you're up.

34:24.562 --> 34:25.897
Tell the judges
about your blade.

34:25.897 --> 34:27.482
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:27.482 --> 34:29.859
<i>- It's all one piece, 5160.</i>

34:29.859 --> 34:31.695
<i>Hand-forged, mostly.</i>

34:31.695 --> 34:34.364
It's ugly, but it'll
mess stuff up.

34:34.364 --> 34:37.158
- Well, gentlemen,
this is the weapons test.

34:37.158 --> 34:39.577
Up first: the kill test.
Doug?

34:39.577 --> 34:41.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:41.621 --> 34:43.039
- To see what kind of
lethal damage

34:43.039 --> 34:45.000
your halberd will do,

34:45.000 --> 34:48.003
we'll take your halberd
and deliver thrusts, hacks,

34:48.003 --> 34:51.506
and attempt to dismount
that dummy with its hook.

34:51.506 --> 34:52.841
Phil, you're up first.
You ready for this?

34:52.841 --> 34:54.342
- Yes, sir.

34:54.342 --> 34:56.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:56.344 --> 34:58.513
Well, Phil, I would love
to test your blade,

34:58.513 --> 35:00.473
but I'm still recovering
from an injury,

35:00.473 --> 35:03.560
so to help me horse around
with your weapon today,

35:03.560 --> 35:06.563
please welcome my brother,
R. J. Marcaida.

35:06.563 --> 35:08.481
<i>- Let's do this.</i>

35:08.481 --> 35:09.983
<i>I spent a long time</i>
<i>making that thing,</i>

35:09.983 --> 35:11.610
and I want to see it work.

35:11.610 --> 35:18.575
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:26.374 --> 35:28.043
- All right, Phil.
Your spear tip

35:28.043 --> 35:30.503
is sharp,
not only at the point,

35:30.503 --> 35:32.130
but its edges also.

35:32.130 --> 35:34.257
Your axe head:
not only did it

35:34.257 --> 35:36.509
dig in and break the ribs,

35:36.509 --> 35:38.511
it went in and cut
the internal organs

35:38.511 --> 35:40.388
that were behind the ribs.

35:40.388 --> 35:43.391
And your hook blade--
it dug into the ribs

35:43.391 --> 35:46.061
and dismounted the dummy
from the horse.

35:46.061 --> 35:48.229
Overall, your weapon here

35:48.229 --> 35:49.564
will kill.

35:49.564 --> 35:51.107
- Thank you.
- Good job.

35:51.107 --> 35:52.317
All right, Johnathan.
You're up next.

35:52.317 --> 35:54.194
You ready?
- Let's do it.

35:54.194 --> 35:56.196
<i>My halberd's a brute.</i>
<i>I'm excited to hear</i>

35:56.196 --> 35:58.156
<i>Doug tell me it'll kill.</i>
<i>That'll make my son happy.</i>

35:58.156 --> 35:59.824
I wanna see some blood
and gore and guts.

35:59.824 --> 36:06.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:16.549 --> 36:18.426
- All right, Johnathan.
On the thrust,

36:18.426 --> 36:20.178
your spear tip right here

36:20.178 --> 36:21.805
penetrated deep

36:21.805 --> 36:24.140
and created
a deep wound channel.

36:24.140 --> 36:25.433
Your axe head here--

36:25.433 --> 36:27.560
Pretty much,
it was just the tip

36:27.560 --> 36:29.312
that penetrated into the chest

36:29.312 --> 36:30.772
and also into the diaphragm.

36:30.772 --> 36:33.066
Your hook broke the ribs,

36:33.066 --> 36:34.901
got into the organs,

36:34.901 --> 36:37.904
and dismounted
the whole dummy from the horse.

36:37.904 --> 36:40.448
The most important thing
about this whole thing is

36:40.448 --> 36:41.825
it will kill.

36:41.825 --> 36:43.618
All right, bladesmiths.

36:43.618 --> 36:44.577
Next up is the strength test.

36:44.577 --> 36:45.620
Ben?

36:45.620 --> 36:47.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:47.580 --> 36:49.457
- To test the strength and
durability of your halberds,

36:49.457 --> 36:50.875
I'll be chopping into

36:50.875 --> 36:52.377
this corrugated sheet steel.

36:52.377 --> 36:54.087
Remember, this test
is all about

36:54.087 --> 36:55.672
what the steel does
to your halberds,

36:55.672 --> 36:57.298
and not what your halberds
do to the steel.

36:57.298 --> 36:58.299
Phil, you're up first.
You ready?

36:58.299 --> 36:59.634
- Yes, sir.

36:59.634 --> 37:06.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.282 --> 37:24.534
- Well, Phil,
your halberd held up perfectly.

37:24.534 --> 37:27.036
All of the faces on it
are still razor-sharp.

37:27.036 --> 37:29.539
There's no deformation
that I can see.

37:29.539 --> 37:30.915
Overall, very well done.

37:30.915 --> 37:32.333
- Thank you.

37:32.333 --> 37:33.752
- Johnathan, you're up.
You ready?

37:33.752 --> 37:36.337
- Get you some.

37:36.337 --> 37:43.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:52.979 --> 37:54.689
- Well, Johnathan,
on the hits,

37:54.689 --> 37:56.065
your edges held up
pretty well.

37:56.065 --> 37:57.817
I don't see any problems
with them.

37:57.817 --> 37:59.486
The one thing
that does concern me is

37:59.486 --> 38:01.696
the blade's taken a bit of
a bend to one side here,

38:01.696 --> 38:03.448
but the edges and the point

38:03.448 --> 38:05.408
seem to have done pretty well
in the penetration.

38:05.408 --> 38:07.619
The whole thing held up.
Still solid.

38:07.619 --> 38:08.870
Well done.

38:08.870 --> 38:10.246
Up next is the sharpness test,

38:10.246 --> 38:11.372
and for that,
I give you to Dave.

38:11.372 --> 38:13.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:13.041 --> 38:14.459
- All right, bladesmiths.

38:14.459 --> 38:15.794
To test the sharpness
of your blades,

38:15.794 --> 38:17.545
I'll be cutting through
these fish

38:17.545 --> 38:20.632
using both the blade
and the tip of your halberds.

38:20.632 --> 38:22.258
Now, a good, sharp blade

38:22.258 --> 38:24.469
should cut through those fish
nice and clean.

38:24.469 --> 38:25.595
Phil, you ready?

38:25.595 --> 38:26.460
- Go for it.

38:29.599 --> 38:32.393
The slicing test
is the scariest one for me,

38:32.393 --> 38:35.313
<i>because the edges</i>
<i>on my halberd are thick.</i>

38:35.313 --> 38:36.773
I don't know how well
they'll do

38:36.773 --> 38:38.691
<i>cutting something fairly soft.</i>

38:38.691 --> 38:45.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.831 --> 38:54.123
- All right.

38:54.123 --> 38:55.917
The cuts look very clean.

38:55.917 --> 38:58.169
They're just nice slices.

38:58.169 --> 38:59.838
I really like
the design of this weapon.

38:59.838 --> 39:02.298
Uh, the handle feels good.

39:02.298 --> 39:04.300
It's got some heft to it,
but it's balanced nicely.

39:04.300 --> 39:05.635
But most off,

39:05.635 --> 39:06.970
it's definitely a sharp weapon.

39:06.970 --> 39:08.471
You built a cutter. Good job.

39:08.471 --> 39:10.014
- Thank you, sir.

39:10.014 --> 39:11.724
- Johnathan, you ready?
- Always.

39:11.724 --> 39:13.810
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:13.810 --> 39:15.687
Phil's blade performed
pretty good in the fish test.

39:15.687 --> 39:17.397
I didn't know
we were gonna cut fish with it.

39:17.397 --> 39:18.648
<i>I'm sweating the geometry.</i>

39:18.648 --> 39:25.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:35.373 --> 39:36.666
- All right, Johnathan,

39:36.666 --> 39:37.959
you went with
actually trying to

39:37.959 --> 39:39.460
forge this
all out of one piece,

39:39.460 --> 39:40.503
which I appreciate,

39:40.503 --> 39:41.671
it's just there's still

39:41.671 --> 39:42.881
a lot of that weight here.

39:42.881 --> 39:44.549
The socket's very, very thick.

39:44.549 --> 39:46.134
It's covered, but you can
feel the edge of it.

39:46.134 --> 39:48.219
The shape--

39:48.219 --> 39:50.638
You see that historically
quite a bit, but for this test,

39:50.638 --> 39:53.850
it's a little harder to find
the sweet spot on that shape.

39:53.850 --> 39:55.476
With that tip being

39:55.476 --> 39:57.270
knocked out of alignment
a little bit,

39:57.270 --> 39:59.397
harder to target,
harder to index,

39:59.397 --> 40:01.274
but it's a good cutter.
Nicely done.

40:01.274 --> 40:04.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:04.152 --> 40:06.362
- Phil, Johnathan,
you've both done

40:06.362 --> 40:08.239
some amazing work
on your German halberds,

40:08.239 --> 40:10.533
and they performed very well
in our weapons tests.

40:10.533 --> 40:12.660
However, in this arena
of competition,

40:12.660 --> 40:15.246
only the best weapon can win,

40:15.246 --> 40:17.582
and our next "Forged in Fire"
champion is...

40:17.582 --> 40:22.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:22.295 --> 40:23.880
Phil.

40:23.880 --> 40:25.632
Congratulations.

40:25.632 --> 40:27.759
You are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:27.759 --> 40:29.218
Johnathan, unfortunately,
your weapon

40:29.218 --> 40:30.720
did not make the cut.

40:30.720 --> 40:33.306
Ben Abbott's
gonna tell you why.

40:33.306 --> 40:35.183
<i>- Johnathan,</i>
<i>at the end of the day,</i>

40:35.183 --> 40:37.685
<i>your halberd was heavy,</i>
<i>more difficult to wield,</i>

40:37.685 --> 40:39.562
and took a bend
in the strength test,

40:39.562 --> 40:42.649
and for those reasons,
we had to let you go.

40:42.649 --> 40:45.944
- Johnathan,
please surrender your weapon.

40:45.944 --> 40:48.071
- I feel honored
to have competed with Phil--

40:48.071 --> 40:50.323
and the other two guys--
in this competition.

40:50.323 --> 40:51.824
Had a good time.

40:51.824 --> 40:54.077
<i>If you do compete in this,</i>

40:54.077 --> 40:55.411
be ready.

40:55.411 --> 40:56.871
<i>Have your skills on-point,</i>

40:56.871 --> 41:00.333
<i>'cause you will be tested.</i>

41:00.333 --> 41:02.001
- Phil, congratulations.

41:02.001 --> 41:03.878
You are our new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:03.878 --> 41:06.422
and that's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

41:06.422 --> 41:08.591
Good job.
Was all the hard work worth it?

41:08.591 --> 41:10.343
- The hard work was worth it.

41:10.343 --> 41:11.427
I'm very pleased
to have been here.

41:11.427 --> 41:13.554
It was wonderful.

41:13.554 --> 41:17.016
- Well, Phil, please present
your weapon to the judges.

41:17.016 --> 41:19.519
- With pleasure.

41:19.519 --> 41:20.687
<i>Phillip Baldwin won,</i>

41:20.687 --> 41:22.271
<i>and Phillip Baldwin</i>

41:22.271 --> 41:24.774
<i>feels very good about winning.</i>

41:24.774 --> 41:26.818
I would not have missed
the experience

41:26.818 --> 41:28.361
<i>of appearing on</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

41:28.361 --> 41:29.779
<i>for anything in the world.</i>

41:29.779 --> 41:30.697
<i>I met some really fine people</i>

41:30.697 --> 41:32.031
I would've never met

41:32.031 --> 41:34.117
in any other circumstances,

41:34.117 --> 41:36.494
<i>and I really thank</i>
<i>my fellow competitors</i>

41:36.494 --> 41:37.787
for being here.

41:37.787 --> 41:43.543
<i>♪ ♪</i>
